be in the kotlin-stdlib-common. I can use either assertj or JUnit assertions, which are already in the existing build. I'll check everything carefully to ensure I’m not using deprecated APIs and design comprehensive tests for the kotlin-stdlib-common. It seems like focusing on this file is the way to go.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning test coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering creating multiple tests to cover various features like Pair, Triple, and KotlinVersion. I'll check if functions like buildList, buildMap, and buildSet were added in version 1.6. They seem stable in the stdlib. I'll also want to verify common stdlib availability for sequences, particularly the sequence builder, which might involve coroutines. I need to ensure I don't reflect or serialize unnecessarily.\\n\\nI should include testing for Regex, string utilities, ranges, and properties while ensuring I’m not duplicating tests from version 1.5.31 since that’s already covered. However, if I’m still on version 1.6.20, some duplication may make sense.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Identifying new test features**\\n\\nI want to make sure I’m not just copying what's already in version 1.5.31 for the same test file. I need to come up with a different set of features that aren't covered yet, focusing on newer APIs or broader common ones. I might inspect the user-code-filter, but that doesn’t seem very relevant. Instead, I'll consider checking the source or jar files, perhaps using listLibraryJars or looking through repository contents for more insights.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reviewing test harness options**\\n\\nI’m thinking I can still use the JDK in the test harness. To maximize coverage of library code, I should utilize standard library features. Maybe a mutable list for callbacks is a better choice than atomic. I’ll check if the Kotlin test file has package paths with underscores. We’ll use the package `org_jetbrains_kotlin.kotlin_stdlib_common`, making sure the class is public. I need to consider whether to import assertj or kotlin-test since my build lacks kotlin-test-junit. Using assertj seems safer since that dependency exists.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Planning test file structure**\\n\\nI'm considering using the edit function to replace the entire file instead of just writing. It seems this would be more efficient, especially since the old text is large and unique. I want to craft the content carefully, including the license header. I also need to confirm the package path and class naming, sticking with `package org_jetbrains_kotlin.kotlin_stdlib_common`. I’ll import AssertJ's `assertThat` and draft a test file with five tests and some small helper types.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering string manipulation**\\n\\nI think I might need to replace part of a string for a better format. Using something like `\\\"org.jetbrains.kotlin:kotlin-stdlib-common\\\".replace(\\\"-stdlib-common\\\", \\\".stdlib.common\\\")` gives me the result of `\\\"org.jetbrains.kotlin:kotlin.stdlib.common\\\"`, which is nice! I'm thinking that maybe it should only replace the suffix if it matches exactly. This could test some lazy evaluation and delegates, which seems like a good approach!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build outputs**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I should inspect the placeholder build outputs or previous tests. But do I really need to do that? It might not be necessary right now. I should focus on editing the file instead. That seems like a more immediate task! Let's see if just editing is enough for what I need or if I should look at those outputs later.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_gJDkDavqwMFcYz9dF4LZ4JQu|fc_0dee2bf28bef362c0169efa2a2ace48191937662adb323f45b", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-stdlib-common/1.6.20/src/test/kotlin/org_jetbrains_kotlin/kotlin_stdlib_common/Kotlin_stdlib_commonTest.kt", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_jetbrains_kotlin.kotlin_stdlib_common\n\nimport org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\nimport kotlin.properties.Delegates\nimport kotlin.time.Duration.Companion.milliseconds\nimport kotlin.time.Duration.Companion.seconds\n\npublic class Kotlin_stdlib_commonTest {\n    @Test\n    fun resultApiTransformsAndRecoversAcrossBranches() {\n        val events = mutableListOf<String>()\n\n        val parsedVersion = runCatching { \"1.6.20\".split('.').map(String::toInt) }\n            .onSuccess { parts -> events += \"parsed:${parts.joinToString(\"-\")}\" }\n            .mapCatching { parts -> parts[0] * 100 + parts[1] * 10 + parts[2] / 10 }\n            .getOrThrow()\n\n        val recoveredVersion = runCatching { \"1.6.x\".split('.').map(String::toInt) }\n            .mapCatching { parts -> parts.sum() }\n            .recover { error ->\n                events += \"recovered:${error.javaClass.simpleName}\"\n                -1\n            }\n            .getOrThrow()\n\n        assertThat(parsedVersion).isEqualTo(162)\n        assertThat(recoveredVersion).isEqualTo(-1)\n        assertThat(events).containsExactly(\n            \"parsed:1-6-20\",\n            \"recovered:NumberFormatException\",\n        )\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    fun collectionBuildersAndWindowingRetainStableOrdering() {\n        val versions = buildList {\n            add(\"1.5.31\")\n            add(\"1.6.20\")\n            add(\"1.7.10\")\n            add(\"1.8.0\")\n        }\n        val labelsByMinor = buildMap {\n            versions.forEach { version ->\n                put(version.substringBeforeLast('.'), \"kotlin-stdlib-common:$version\")\n            }\n        }\n        val supportedMinors = buildSet {\n            addAll(versions.map { version -> version.substringBeforeLast('.') })\n        }\n        val upgradePath = versions.zipWithNext { from, to -> \"$from->$to\" }\n        val releaseWindows = versions.windowed(size = 2, step = 2, partialWindows = true)\n\n        assertThat(labelsByMinor).containsEntry(\"1.6\", \"kotlin-stdlib-common:1.6.20\")\n        assertThat(supportedMinors).containsExactly(\"1.5\", \"1.6\", \"1.7\", \"1.8\")\n        assertThat(upgradePath).containsExactly(\n            \"1.5.31->1.6.20\",\n            \"1.6.20->1.7.10\",\n            \"1.7.10->1.8.0\",\n        )\n        assertThat(releaseWindows).containsExactly(\n            listOf(\"1.5.31\", \"1.6.20\"),\n            listOf(\"1.7.10\", \"1.8.0\"),\n        )\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    fun delegatedPropertiesAndLazyValuesTrackStateChanges() {\n        val moduleState = ModuleState()\n\n        assertThat(moduleState.events).isEmpty()\n        assertThat(moduleState.normalizedCoordinate).isEqualTo(\"org.jetbrains.kotlin:kotlin.stdlib.common\")\n\n        moduleState.releaseChannel = \"rc\"\n        moduleState.releaseChannel = \"stable\"\n        moduleState.priority = 4\n        moduleState.priority = 2\n\n        assertThat(moduleState.releaseChannel).isEqualTo(\"stable\")\n        assertThat(moduleState.priority).isEqualTo(4)\n        assertThat(moduleState.events).containsExactly(\n            \"lazy:normalize\",\n            \"channel:draft->rc\",\n            \"channel:rc->stable\",\n            \"priority:accepted:0->4\",\n            \"priority:rejected:4->2\",\n        )\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    fun sequencePipelinesStayLazyAndSupportScopedConsumption() {\n        val trace = mutableListOf<String>()\n        val generatedVersions = sequence {\n            for (minor in 5..7) {\n                trace += \"yield:$minor\"\n                yield(minor)\n            }\n        }.map { minor ->\n            trace += \"map:$minor\"\n            \"1.$minor.20\"\n        }\n\n        assertThat(trace).isEmpty()\n\n        val firstTwo = generatedVersions.take(2).toList()\n        val minorLabels = sequenceOf(\"1.5.31\", \"1.6.20\", \"1.7.10\")\n            .map { version -> version.substringBeforeLast('.') }\n            .distinct()\n            .toList()\n\n        assertThat(firstTwo).containsExactly(\"1.5.20\", \"1.6.20\")\n        assertThat(trace).containsExactly(\n            \"yield:5\",\n            \"map:5\",\n            \"yield:6\",\n            \"map:6\",\n        )\n        assertThat(minorLabels).containsExactly(\"1.5\", \"1.6\", \"1.7\")\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    fun durationArithmeticAndStringBuildersSummarizeTheTestMatrix() {\n        val startupBudget = 750.milliseconds + 2.seconds\n        val report = buildString {\n            append(\"group=org.jetbrains.kotlin\\n\")\n            append(\"artifact=kotlin-stdlib-common\\n\")\n            append(\"version=1.6.20\")\n        }\n        val normalizedReport = report.lineSequence()\n            .map { line ->\n                val key = line.substringBefore('=').uppercase()\n                val value = line.substringAfter('=')\n                \"$key:$value\"\n            }\n            .joinToString(separator = \" | \")\n\n        assertThat(startupBudget.inWholeMilliseconds).isEqualTo(2750)\n        assertThat((startupBudget - 250.milliseconds).inWholeSeconds).isEqualTo(2)\n        assertThat(normalizedReport).isEqualTo(\n            \"GROUP:org.jetbrains.kotlin | ARTIFACT:kotlin-stdlib-common | VERSION:1.6.20\",\n        )\n    }\n}\n\nprivate class ModuleState {\n    val events = mutableListOf<String>()\n\n    val normalizedCoordinate: String by lazy {\n        events += \"lazy:normalize\"\n        \"org.jetbrains.kotlin:kotlin-stdlib-common\".replace(\"-stdlib-common\", \".stdlib.common\")\n    }\n\n    var releaseChannel: String by Delegates.observable(\"draft\") { _, oldValue, newValue ->\n        events += \"channel:$oldValue->$newValue\"\n    }\n\n    var priority: Int by Delegates.veto